posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>1306482
mpv --sub-file=/path/to/sub
You can also just copy the subtitle to the folder the video is located and rename the sub so that it matches the video's filename. This way the sub is automatically loaded every time you open the video file.

if I were in the Movie directory and typed "mpv --sub-file=/Desktop/sub/gnfos.ass" Would that be right? Would be all I had to do? Could I type "mpv options gnfos.mp4 now and see my subtitle available for me to select?

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>1306800
If the file is on a different location from the current working directory, you generally have to type out the full path.

> if I were in the Movie directory and typed "mpv --sub-file=/Desktop/sub/gnfos.ass"
Yes. But note that while I'm not sure what distribution you are using, the desktop is usually located in ~/Desktop. Haven't heard of one where it's located in /Desktop.

> Could I type "mpv options gnfos.mp4 now and see my subtitle available for me to select?
It depends on your current directory, but this snippet should work anywhere (assuming the location of the desktop is ~/Desktop):
mpv --sub-file=~/Desktop/sub/gnfos.ass ~/Desktop/Movie/gnfos.mp4

You can assume wlog that the point is on the first ellipse, otherwise use a' = a+n, b' = b+n, and a negative n' = -n.

First you need to write the parametric equation of the first ellipse:
x = a cos t
y = b sin t
t in [0, 2 pi)

(x0,y0) is a point of the first ellipse corresponding to parameter say t0 (= angle of your green line).
x0 = a cos t0
y0 = b sin t0

Your two points are P1 = (x0, y0 + d1) with the same x0 coordinate as the first point and P2 = (x0+d2,y0) with the same y0 coordinate, so you just need to calculate d1 and d2 by using the parametrization of the second ellipse.

P1:
x0 = (a+n) cos t1
y0 + d1 = (b+n) sin t1
The first equation gives
cos t1 = x0/(a+n)
t1 = arccos x0/(a+n)
Now you can use it in the second equation to calculate d1 and ultimately the distance of P1 to O.

Same with P2 (using first the equation with y0).

>>1306184
it depends on what you want to measure and how you measure it. In any case, you should use the term line segment instead of line (which is infinite).

The first segment is in any case larger (as a set) since it contains all points of the second segment and additionally all points corresponding to (1,2] which are missing in the second segment.

On the other hand, there is a one-to-one (bijective) mapping between the points of the first segment and the points of the second segment, so their cardinalities (number of elements) are equal (namely the cardinality of the set of the real numbers |R| = 2^|N|). That's different from finite sets, where a larger set has always a larger cardinality.

If you measure the lengths of the segments, then the first one has a length of 2 and the second one of 1. If you measure the area, then both have an area of 0.

And so on. So you really need to specify what you mean with "longer". In the usual sense, length of a segment is the distance between its end-points, so
